Welcome to lesson 4 on functions and exceptions.

2

00:00:03,480  -->  00:00:06,280
The last lesson in our PCP course,

3

00:00:06,280  -->  00:00:10,420
where we'll be diving into the methodologies and patterns for making

4

00:00:10,420  -->  00:00:15,040
our Python code come to life almost as if by magic.

5

00:00:15,040  -->  00:00:18,380
Imagine after a long day of coding in Python,

6

00:00:18,380  -->  00:00:21,240
you become quite hungry and wander over to

7

00:00:21,240  -->  00:00:25,020
the kitchen to cook yourself some food in order to refuel.

8

00:00:25,020  -->  00:00:29,970
You pull up a recipe on your phone and start following each step one by one.

9

00:00:29,970  -->  00:00:34,160
Perhaps, you'll need to add in some ingredients,

10

00:00:34,160  -->  00:00:35,780
sprinkle in some spices,

11

00:00:35,780  -->  00:00:38,740
mix in vegetables, or combine other mix ins.

12

00:00:38,740  -->  00:00:40,640
Bring them all together in certain ways,

13

00:00:40,640  -->  00:00:42,980
prepare the wet and dry ingredients separately,

14

00:00:42,980  -->  00:00:48,340
and/or together, put certain foods on the grill or into the oven to bake,

15

00:00:48,340  -->  00:00:50,085
and so on and so forth.

16

00:00:50,085  -->  00:00:51,850
To give another example,

17

00:00:51,850  -->  00:00:53,590
imagine you're assembling a car,

18

00:00:53,590  -->  00:00:57,125
and you need to put a lot of various pieces together.

19

00:00:57,125  -->  00:01:02,110
Instead in doing each step manually every single time.

20

00:01:02,110  -->  00:01:08,130
You have a machine that knows how to do the assembly once you give it instructions.

21

00:01:08,130  -->  00:01:10,770
The machine can follow the instructions with

22

00:01:10,770  -->  00:01:14,010
near perfect precision and accuracy every time,

23

00:01:14,010  -->  00:01:18,740
ensuring each car in the assembly line comes out the same.

24

00:01:18,740  -->  00:01:21,100
In the world of Python programming,

25

00:01:21,100  -->  00:01:24,080
we have something similar to recipes called functions.

26

00:01:24,080  -->  00:01:28,180
Functions are like those detailed steps in a recipe,

27

00:01:28,180  -->  00:01:33,140
allowing us to break down complex problems into manageable pieces.

28

00:01:33,140  -->  00:01:34,980
They help us write clearer,

29

00:01:34,980  -->  00:01:38,120
reusable and more organized code.

30

00:01:38,120  -->  00:01:43,120
They can also help us follow a specific flow or layout of, if this,

31

00:01:43,120  -->  00:01:46,540
then that or if this or that,

32

00:01:46,540  -->  00:01:50,480
helping us stay logical, precise, and methodical.

33

00:01:50,480  -->  00:01:53,820
Functions and Python act as these machines.

34

00:01:53,820  -->  00:01:57,200
Once created, they allow you to reuse code,

35

00:01:57,200  -->  00:01:59,040
break your programs into smaller,

36

00:01:59,040  -->  00:02:02,570
manageable pieces, and even handle complex logic.

37

00:02:02,570  -->  00:02:05,660
But what happens if your machine encounters an issue,

38

00:02:05,660  -->  00:02:08,600
like a missing part for the car in the assembly line?

39

00:02:08,600  -->  00:02:12,500
Or you're missing an ingredient for your delicious dinner.

40

00:02:12,500  -->  00:02:16,300
If a recipe is missing an ingredient or a crucial baking step,

41

00:02:16,300  -->  00:02:19,040
this can spell disaster for the meal.

42

00:02:19,040  -->  00:02:21,560
Or if the car is not assembled correctly,

43

00:02:21,560  -->  00:02:24,980
because the assembly line forgot to include different crucial steps,

44

00:02:24,980  -->  00:02:27,235
the car might not come out correctly.

45

00:02:27,235  -->  00:02:30,240
This is where exceptions come into play.

46

00:02:30,240  -->  00:02:35,460
Python allows you to detect and manage unexpected situations ensuring that

47

00:02:35,460  -->  00:02:41,520
your program continues running smoothly or handles errors gracefully?

48

